2026-06-30 | Number of Substrings Containing All Three Characters

	Question
Return the total number of substrings containing all three characters.
	Key Insight
Use a Sliding Window.
Maintain a window:
		[left...right]
and keep the frequency of:
		a
		b
		c
Whenever the current window contains all three characters:
		freq[a] > 0
		freq[b] > 0
		freq[c] > 0
then every substring starting at left and ending at:
		right,
		right+1,
		...
		n-1
is also valid.
So we can directly add:
		n - right
to the answer.
Then shrink the window from the left.
	Approach
1.	Maintain two pointers:
			left
			right
2.	Expand the window by moving right.
3.	Update frequencies.
4.	While all three characters exist:
			answer += n - right
			remove s[left]
			left++
5.	Return answer.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int numberOfSubstrings(string s) {
        vector<int> freq(3, 0);
        int left = 0;
        int ans = 0;
        int n = s.size();
        for(int right = 0; right < n; right++) {
            freq[s[right] - 'a']++;
            while(freq[0] > 0 &&
                  freq[1] > 0 &&
                  freq[2] > 0) {
                ans += n - right;
                freq[s[left] - 'a']--;
                left++;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
	Example
	Input:
		s = "abcabc"
	Valid substrings include:
		"abc"
		"abca"
		"abcab"
		"abcabc"
		"bca"
		...
	Output:
		10
	Key Insight
	Once a window contains at least one `'a'`, `'b'`, and `'c'`, extending its right boundary can never make it invalid. Therefore, for every valid window ending at `right`, there are exactly `n - right` valid substrings starting at the current `left`, leading to an O(n) sliding window solution.
